      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Online Drift Signals"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Cheap to compute per-request, available in real-time, no external model call required:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Output Length Distribution"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Length is the most reliable first-order drift indicator. A model that starts generating 20% shorter responses on average has changed significantly. Track the histogram of output token counts, not just the mean:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import numpy as np\nfrom prometheus_client import Histogram\n\nOUTPUT_LEN = Histogram(\n    \"llm_output_length_tokens\",\n    \"Histogram of output token counts\",\n    [\"model\"],\n    buckets=[10, 25, 50, 100, 200, 400, 800, 1600, 3200],\n)\n\ndef record_completion(model: str, output_tokens: int):\n    OUTPUT_LEN.labels(model=model).observe(output_tokens)\n\n# PromQL: median output length (compare today vs 7-day baseline)\n# histogram_quantile(0.50, sum(rate(llm_output_length_tokens_bucket[1h])) by (le))"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Type-Token Ratio (Vocabulary Diversity)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "TTR measures lexical diversity \u2014 how many unique words appear per total words. A drop in TTR signals the model is repeating itself more or using a narrower vocabulary:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\text{TTR} = \\frac{|\\text{unique tokens}|}{|\\text{total tokens}|}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def type_token_ratio(text: str) -> float:\n    tokens = text.lower().split()\n    if not tokens:\n        return 0.0\n    return len(set(tokens)) / len(tokens)\n\n# Sliding window: compute TTR over the last 1000 responses\n# Alert if rolling median TTR drops > 15% from 7-day baseline"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Refusal Rate"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "An increase in refusal rate (model declining to answer) after a model update or policy change is a critical drift signal:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "REFUSAL_PHRASES = [\n    \"i cannot\", \"i can't\", \"i'm unable to\", \"i'm not able to\",\n    \"i won't\", \"i must decline\", \"i'm sorry, but i cannot\",\n    \"as an ai\", \"it would be inappropriate\",\n]\n\ndef is_refusal(text: str) -> bool:\n    lower = text.lower()\n    return any(phrase in lower for phrase in REFUSAL_PHRASES)\n\nfrom prometheus_client import Counter\nREFUSAL_COUNTER = Counter(\"llm_refusals_total\", \"Refusal responses\", [\"model\"])\nTOTAL_COUNTER = Counter(\"llm_completions_total\", \"Total completions\", [\"model\"])\n\ndef record_completion_quality(model: str, text: str):\n    TOTAL_COUNTER.labels(model=model).inc()\n    if is_refusal(text):\n        REFUSAL_COUNTER.labels(model=model).inc()\n\n# PromQL: refusal rate\n# rate(llm_refusals_total[1h]) / rate(llm_completions_total[1h])"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "N-gram Repetition Ratio"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Repetition is a common failure mode in quantised or fine-tuned models. Track the ratio of repeated 4-grams in the output:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from collections import Counter as Ctr\n\ndef ngram_repetition_ratio(text: str, n: int = 4) -> float:\n    words = text.split()\n    if len(words) < n:\n        return 0.0\n    ngrams = [tuple(words[i:i+n]) for i in range(len(words) - n + 1)]\n    counts = Ctr(ngrams)\n    repeated = sum(c - 1 for c in counts.values() if c > 1)\n    return repeated / len(ngrams)\n\n# ratio > 0.15 \u2192 likely repetition loop\n# vLLM catches most loops before finish, but partial loops still appear"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Statistical Drift Detection"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Population Stability Index (PSI)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "PSI measures how much a feature distribution has shifted between a reference window (e.g. last 7 days) and the current window. It is common in traditional ML monitoring and applies directly to LLM output features:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\text{PSI} = \\sum_{i=1}^{N} \\left( p_i - q_i \\right) \\ln\\left(\\frac{p_i}{q_i}\\right)"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "where "
          },
          {
            "type": "inlineMath",
            "attrs": {
              "latex": "p_i"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is the fraction of observations in bucket "
          },
          {
            "type": "inlineMath",
            "attrs": {
              "latex": "i"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " in the reference window and "
          },
          {
            "type": "inlineMath",
            "attrs": {
              "latex": "q_i"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is the current window. PSI < 0.1 is stable, 0.1\u20130.2 is moderate shift (investigate), > 0.2 is severe drift (alert)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import numpy as np\n\ndef psi(reference: np.ndarray, current: np.ndarray, bins: int = 10) -> float:\n    ref_counts, edges = np.histogram(reference, bins=bins)\n    cur_counts, _ = np.histogram(current, bins=edges)\n\n    # Avoid zero division: clip to small positive\n    ref_pct = np.clip(ref_counts / ref_counts.sum(), 1e-6, None)\n    cur_pct = np.clip(cur_counts / cur_counts.sum(), 1e-6, None)\n\n    return float(np.sum((cur_pct - ref_pct) * np.log(cur_pct / ref_pct)))\n\n# Example: output length drift detection\nreference_lengths = np.random.normal(180, 40, 5000)   # baseline\ncurrent_lengths   = np.random.normal(140, 40, 1000)   # shorter outputs today\n\nscore = psi(reference_lengths, current_lengths)\nprint(f\"PSI = {score:.3f}\")   # ~0.15 \u2192 moderate drift, investigate\nif score > 0.2:\n    print(\"ALERT: significant output length drift detected\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Kolmogorov-Smirnov Test"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The KS test detects whether two samples come from the same continuous distribution, without requiring binning. Use it for output length and sentiment score:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from scipy import stats\nimport numpy as np\n\ndef ks_drift_test(reference: np.ndarray, current: np.ndarray,\n                  threshold: float = 0.05) -> dict:\n    statistic, p_value = stats.ks_2samp(reference, current)\n    return {\n        \"statistic\": round(statistic, 4),\n        \"p_value\":   round(p_value, 4),\n        \"drift\":     p_value < threshold,\n    }\n\n# Run hourly on the last 1000 responses vs 7-day reference\nreference = np.load(\"baseline_output_lengths.npy\")\ncurrent   = np.array(recent_output_lengths[-1000:])\nresult = ks_drift_test(reference, current)\nif result[\"drift\"]:\n    alert(f\"KS test: output length distribution shifted (p={result['p_value']})\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "EWMA Control Chart"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Exponentially Weighted Moving Average control charts detect gradual shifts in a scalar metric (e.g. mean output length) faster than static thresholds. The EWMA statistic at time "
          },
          {
            "type": "inlineMath",
            "attrs": {
              "latex": "t"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "Z_t = \\lambda \\bar{x}_t + (1 - \\lambda) Z_{t-1}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "where "
          },
          {
            "type": "inlineMath",
            "attrs": {
              "latex": "\\lambda"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " controls how much weight recent observations get (typically 0.1\u20130.3). Alert when "
          },
          {
            "type": "inlineMath",
            "attrs": {
              "latex": "|Z_t - \\mu_0| > k \\sigma"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " where "
          },
          {
            "type": "inlineMath",
            "attrs": {
              "latex": "\\mu_0"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is the baseline mean and "
          },
          {
            "type": "inlineMath",
            "attrs": {
              "latex": "k"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is typically 3 (3-sigma control)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "class EWMAChart:\n    def __init__(self, baseline_mean: float, baseline_std: float,\n                 lam: float = 0.2, k: float = 3.0):\n        self.mu0 = baseline_mean\n        self.sigma = baseline_std\n        self.lam = lam\n        self.k = k\n        self.z = baseline_mean   # initialise at baseline\n\n    def update(self, x: float) -> bool:\n        self.z = self.lam * x + (1 - self.lam) * self.z\n        ucl = self.mu0 + self.k * self.sigma * (self.lam / (2 - self.lam)) ** 0.5\n        lcl = self.mu0 - self.k * self.sigma * (self.lam / (2 - self.lam)) ** 0.5\n        return self.z > ucl or self.z < lcl   # True = out of control\n\nchart = EWMAChart(baseline_mean=180, baseline_std=40)\nfor length in recent_output_lengths:\n    if chart.update(length):\n        alert(\"EWMA drift: output length out of control limits\")\n        break"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Embedding-Based Drift"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Lightweight statistical features (length, TTR) detect surface-level drift. For semantic drift \u2014 the model saying the same number of words but about different topics or with different reasoning quality \u2014 you need embeddings."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import numpy as np\nfrom sentence_transformers import SentenceTransformer\n\nmodel = SentenceTransformer(\"all-MiniLM-L6-v2\")   # fast, 80MB\n\ndef semantic_drift_score(reference_texts: list[str],\n                         current_texts: list[str]) -> float:\n    ref_embeds = model.encode(reference_texts, batch_size=64, normalize_embeddings=True)\n    cur_embeds = model.encode(current_texts,   batch_size=64, normalize_embeddings=True)\n\n    ref_centroid = ref_embeds.mean(axis=0)\n    cur_centroid = cur_embeds.mean(axis=0)\n\n    # Cosine distance between centroid clusters\n    cosine_sim = float(np.dot(ref_centroid, cur_centroid))\n    return 1 - cosine_sim   # 0 = identical, higher = more drift\n\n# Run nightly on 1000-sample windows\nscore = semantic_drift_score(baseline_outputs, recent_outputs)\nif score > 0.05:\n    alert(f\"Semantic drift detected: cosine distance = {score:.3f}\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A cosine distance above 0.05 between reference and current output centroids (sampled from the same request types) indicates meaningful semantic shift. Compute this nightly on 1,000 sampled pairs rather than every request \u2014 embedding encoding at scale is expensive."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Offline Evaluation Pipeline"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Online signals catch distribution shifts. Offline evaluation measures whether quality actually changed. Run offline evaluation on a sampled 1\u20135% of production traffic:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "LLM-as-Judge"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import asyncio, httpx, random\n\nJUDGE_PROMPT = \"\"\"Compare these two model responses to the same query.\nRate the CURRENT response vs the REFERENCE response on:\n1. Accuracy (1-5)\n2. Completeness (1-5)\n3. Clarity (1-5)\n\nQuery: {query}\nReference response: {reference}\nCurrent response: {current}\n\nReply with JSON: {{\"accuracy\": N, \"completeness\": N, \"clarity\": N, \"verdict\": \"better|same|worse\"}}\"\"\"\n\nasync def judge_pair(query: str, reference: str, current: str,\n                     judge_client: httpx.AsyncClient) -> dict:\n    prompt = JUDGE_PROMPT.format(query=query, reference=reference, current=current)\n    r = await judge_client.post(\"/v1/chat/completions\", json={\n        \"model\": \"meta-llama/Llama-3-70b-instruct\",  # separate judge model\n        \"messages\": [{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": prompt}],\n        \"response_format\": {\"type\": \"json_object\"},\n        \"max_tokens\": 100,\n    })\n    return r.json()[\"choices\"][0][\"message\"][\"content\"]\n\n# Sample 1% of production logs; pair with cached reference outputs\nasync def run_offline_eval(production_logs: list[dict], sample_rate: float = 0.01):\n    sample = random.sample(production_logs, int(len(production_logs) * sample_rate))\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient(base_url=\"http://judge-model\") as client:\n        tasks = [judge_pair(l[\"query\"], l[\"reference_output\"], l[\"current_output\"], client)\n                 for l in sample]\n        return await asyncio.gather(*tasks)"
          }
        ]
      },
